suffering for eight

481
00:30:31,989 --> 00:30:33,641
years. I'm not gonna
help you make it worse.

482
00:30:33,665 --> 00:30:35,827
I'm not gonna help
you make it interesting.

483
00:30:35,901 --> 00:30:38,769
That's okay. Foreman's
better at that stuff than you are.

484
00:30:39,438 --> 00:30:43,341
We need five-millimeter cuts through
the occipital and hypothalamic regions.

485
00:30:44,176 --> 00:30:45,769
No.

486
00:30:54,686 --> 00:30:56,746
How many millimeters?

487
00:30:59,157 --> 00:31:01,058
I can help him.

488
00:31:01,126 --> 00:31:03,288
That's it? That's your argument?

489
00:31:03,362 --> 00:31:05,058
It seems like a good one.

490
00:31:05,130 --> 00:31:08,042
If I thought for a second you wanted
to help him, you'd have carte blanche.

491
00:31:08,066 --> 00:31:10,092
You're doing this
because it's fun.

492
00:31:10,168 --> 00:31:11,693
Does nobody in this hospital

493
00:31:11,770 --> 00:31:13,748
have anything better to
talk about than my motives?

494
00:31:13,772 --> 00:31:15,383
My motives have nothing
to do with the case.

495
00:31:15,407 --> 00:31:17,672
Your motives have everything
to do with your judgment.

496
00:31:17,743 --> 00:31:19,983
For the first time in years, I
got no opiates in my body.

497
00:31:20,011 --> 00:31:21,274
Now you question my judgment?

498
00:31:21,346 --> 00:31:23,906
Twenty-four times a year, you
come storming into my office,

499
00:31:23,982 --> 00:31:27,510
spouting that you can help someone,
only you never say those words.

500
00:31:27,586 --> 00:31:29,179
You say something like,

501
00:31:29,254 --> 00:31:33,157
"His pancreas is gonna explode
because his brain is on fire."

502
00:31:33,225 --> 00:31:35,785
You come here with
medicine, not with platitudes.

503
00:31:36,261 --> 00:31:37,923
I didn't wanna bore
you with the details.

504
00:31:37,996 --> 00:31:40,966
There are no details.
You have a hunch.

505
00:31:41,466 --> 00:31:45,494
House, you don't use hunches.
You always have reasons.

506
00:31:46,204 --> 00:31:49,732
This hospital doesn't exist
for your whims. I'm sorry.

507
00:31:50,742 --> 00:31:53,974
As of 7:00 a.m. tomorrow morning,
I'm sending your patient home.

508
00:32:01,987 --> 00:32:03,421
The answer's no.

509
00:32:03,488 --> 00:32:07,220
Cuddy called 30 seconds after you
left and said you'd try an end-around.

510
00:32:22,507 --> 00:32:24,237
My leg hurt.

511
00:32:26,912 --> 00:32:27,971
How bad?

512
00:32:28,046 --> 00:32:29,275
Enough that I'm telling you.

513
00:32:30,682 --> 00:32:32,412
Did it go away?

514
00:32:32,484 --> 00:32:34,282
Ached for a while.

515
00:32:36,655 --> 00:32:39,352
First time I've felt anything
there since the surgery.

516
00:32:40,592 --> 00:32:42,561
But it went away?

517
00:32:43,895 --> 00:32:46,729
It was muscular. There
was some cramping.

518
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:51,094
What are you smiling about?

519
00:32:52,904 --> 00:32:54,668
You're 40-something years old.

520
00:32:54,739 --> 00:32:56,739
You've been running God
knows how many miles a day,

521
00:32:56,808 --> 00:33:00,267
fallen a hundred times off that skateboard,
and you're shocked to have some soreness?

522
00:33:00,345 --> 00:33:01,813
Just give me a prescription.

523
00:33:01,880 --> 00:33:03,246
For Vicodin?

524
00:33:03,315 --> 00:33:05,910
House, people get
aching joints, cramps.

525
00:33:05,984 --> 00:33:08,215
They put on an ice pack.
They take some ibuprofen.

526
00:33:08,286 --> 00:33:10,278
I know what the pangs
of middle age feel like.

527
00:33:10,355 --> 00:33:13,223
No, you don't because
you've been stuffing Vicodin

528
00:33:13,291 --> 00:33:15,136
every five minutes since
you turned middle-aged.

529
00:33:15,160 --> 00:33:16,526
The surgery didn't work.

530
00:33:16,595 --> 00:33:18,063
Don't play me.

531
00:33:18,463 --> 00:33:19,829
You think this is a scam?

532
00:33:19,898 --> 00:33:21,764
I think you want me
to feel sorry for you

533
00:33:21,833 --> 00:33:24,701
and either do the end-around
on Cuddy or give you the drugs.

534
00:33:28,507 --> 00:33:31,272
Either way, you get the
high you think you need.

535
00:33:35,914 --> 00:33:38,962
House, your surgery
worked. You're fine. It's

536
00:33:38,986 --> 00:33:41,785
just gonna take time
for it to feel good.

537
00:35:14,546 --> 00:35:17,675
Circumventricular
system senses cytokines

538
00:35:17,749 --> 00:35:20,150
released in the early stages
of the immune response,

539
00:35:20,218 --> 00:35:22,084
but CVOS releases prostaglandins

540
00:35:22,153 --> 00:35:24,520
that reset the hypothalamic
set point upward

541
00:35:24,589 --> 00:35:28,788
unless it's countered by antipyretic
therapy, so, yeah, his brain is on fire.

542
00:35:29,628 --> 00:35:32,097
The suicide attempt
was not a suicide attempt.

543
00:35:32,163 --> 00:35:33,688
He drove that
wheelchair into the pool

544
00:35:33,765 --> 00:35:36,166
because he couldn't
regulate his body temperature.

545
00:35:36,234 --> 00:35:38,567
He had a hypothalamic
dysregulation.

546
00:35:39,170 --> 00:35:44,734
And you discovered this when
you stepped into the university pool?

547
00:35:45,310 --> 00:35:47,802
Fountain. I can cure him.

548
00:35:47,879 --> 00:35:49,108
Cure him!

549
00:35:49,180 --> 00:35:51,149
Even if the fountain
proved anything,

550
00:35:51,216 --> 00:35:54,152
fixing hypothalamic dysregulation
isn't gonna regenerate brain.

551
00:35:54,219 --> 00:35:56,654
No, but if the scar tissue
on his hypothalamus

552
00:35:56,721 --> 00:35:58,280
is resting against
the pituitary,

553
00:35:58,356 --> 00:36:01,190
the adrenals would shut
down. Addison's disease.

554
00:36:01,259 --> 00:36:04,024
You didn't see any scar tissue
on his MRI, his CT scans...

555
00:36:04,095 --> 00:36:06,496
His brain is functional.
His temperature's normal.

556
00:36:06,564 --> 00:36:09,500
There is nothing wrong with
his hypothalamus or his pituitary!

557
00:36:09,567 --> 00:36:12,799
I can make him walk. I can
make him talk. This is a wild guess

558
00:36:12,871 --> 00:36:15,602
that came to you because
you were sweating.

559
00:36:15,674 --> 00:36:19,133
Inject him with cortisol. The guy
will have sex with his wife again.

560
00:36:19,210 --> 00:36:24,046
He'll hug his kid again. Hopefully,
that's the combination he was using.

561
00:36:24,115 --> 00:36:26,675
It'd be a shame if I
had cured a pedophile.

562
00:36:28,119 --> 00:36:30,179
You're smiling.
That's a bad sign.

563
00:36:30,255 --> 00:36:31,621
You're high.

564
00:36:31,690 --> 00:36:33,690
I told you, I haven't had
anything in three months.

565
00:36:33,725 --> 00:36:35,717
This is as high as you get,

566
00:36:35,794 --> 00:36:39,356
a theory that ties your
case up in a neat little bow,

567
00:36:39,431 --> 00:36:42,424
but you don't have a lick
of substantiating proof.

568
00:36:45,503 --> 00:36:49,941
Your decision doesn't make any sense.
There is no risk to a cortisol injection.

569
00:36:50,041 --> 00:36:51,942
If I'm wrong, big deal.

570
00:36:52,010 --> 00:36:54,422
He goes home a vegetable
like he already is, but if I'm right...

571
00:36:54,446 --> 00:36:57,507
This is not about downsides
or risk management.

572
00:36:58,416 --> 00:37:01,443
It is a big deal for you to
understand the word "No."

573
00:37:03,822 --> 00:37:05,814
I'm sorry, House.

574
00:37:30,648 --> 00:37:32,583
He's on his way out of here.

575
00:37:32,650 --> 00:37:35,210
I figured you'd be on your
scooter, racing down the halls

576
00:37:35,286 --> 00:37:38,017
to stab the patient in
the neck with cortisol.

577
00:37:39,891 --> 00:37:42,190
She was right to say no.

578
00:37:43,027 --> 00:37:45,997
I had no objective reason
to think that I was right.

579
00:37:47,899 --> 00:37:50,130
Just needed the puzzle.

580
00:38:04,249 --> 00:38:05,444
Hold on a sec.

581
00:38:05,517 --> 00:38:07,986
Is everything all right?

582
00:38:09,521 --> 00:38:12,320
Yeah, it's just
something I forgot.

583
00:38:24,569 --> 00:38:26,299
What's that?

584
00:38:26,371 --> 00:38:30,968
This is cortisol, and
it's to fight infection.

585
00:38:33,678 --> 00:38:36,910
Want to hold onto that?
Let's put a bandage on it.

586
00:38:55,800 --> 00:38:57,826
Is he okay?

587
00:39:01,840 --> 00:39:02,840
Yes.

588
00:39:02,907 --> 00:39:04,535
Can we go now?

589
00:39:04,609 --> 00:39:06,635
You can go.

590
00:39:16,154 --> 00:39:17,816
Excuse me.

591
00:39:44,782 --> 00:39:46,410
Richard. Richard.

592
00:39:52,390 --> 00:39:54,382
Dad, you okay?

593
00:40:03,635 --> 00:40:06,605
Richard? Richard! Richard!

594
00:40:08,072 --> 00:40:10,064
Richard!

595
00:40:11,676 --> 00:40:13,702
Richard.

596
00:40:20,952 --> 00:40:24,946
Richard, you're standing.

597
00:40:48,546 --> 00:40:50,538
Thank you.

598
00:41:02,160 --> 00:41:03,184
<i>He got up.</i>

599
00:41:04,862 --> 00:41:06,057
I have to go tell House.

600
00:41:06,130 --> 00:41:09,828
No. Cuddy, you can't tell him.

601
00:41:10,535 --> 00:41:12,299
I have to tell
him. He was right.

602
00:41:12,370 --> 00:41:15,135
Why did you do it? Why did
you think he might be right?

603
00:41:16,207 --> 00:41:17,641
Because he's House.

604
00:41:17,709 --> 00:41:19,940
Medically, what made
you think he was right?

605
00:41:21,212 --> 00:41:24,546
Nothing. He got lucky.
That's all that happened.

606
00:41:25,650 --> 00:41:28,119
Telling him no was a good thing

607
00:41:28,186 --> 00:41:31,247
because next time, he won't
get lucky. He'll kill someone.

608
00:41:32,824 --> 00:41:36,283
Just because he was right
doesn't mean he wasn't wrong.

609
00:41:43,568 --> 00:41:46,504
I see him every
day. I can't just...

610
00:41:47,672 --> 00:41:49,197
Everybody lies.
